      "question": "The graph of a polynomial $p(x) = ax^2 + bx + c$ intersects the $x$-axis at exactly one point, which is $(3, 0)$. Given that the polynomial passes through the point $(0, 9)$, determine the value of the leading coefficient $a$ and the number of distinct zeros of the polynomial.",
      "answer": "a = 1, number of distinct zeros = 1",
      "solution": {
        "steps": [
          "Since the graph intersects the x-axis at only one point $(3, 0)$, the polynomial has equal real roots, so it is of the form $p(x) = a(x - 3)^2$.",
          "Substitute the point $(0, 9)$ into the equation to find $a$: $9 = a(0 - 3)^2 \\Rightarrow 9 = 9a \\Rightarrow a = 1$. The number of distinct zeros is 1 as the graph touches the x-axis at a single point."
        ],
        "derivation": "$p(x) = a(x - h)^2 \\\\ p(x) = a(x - 3)^2 \\\\ 9 = a(0 - 3)^2 \\\\ 9 = 9a \\\\ a = 1 \\\\ \\text{Since the graph touches at one point, it has only 1 distinct zero.}$"
      },
